english:
  title: Record of the Wuwu Hall at Lingju Temple
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The teachings of Buddhism came from beyond our borders, yet they have surpassed the teachings native to our land and stand alone in honor. Why is this? Because the people of this land have made it so. Their doctrine of karma and retribution has moved people's hearts, and those who follow Buddhism are generally those who reject the ordinary, despise the vulgar, and find no pleasure in the constraints of Confucian propriety and rule. These are people of exceptional talent. It is no wonder that Buddhism, having attracted such worthy persons, has gained respect in the world. For this reason, I do not utterly reject Buddhism, and sometimes I even hold it in regard—for there is indeed something to be valued in it.

    Now the Great Zen Master Seo of Caoxi, having newly received imperial favor, leads the nine mountains. When he presented himself before the king by the Lo River and was granted an honored seat, it was truly glorious. Yet observing his virtue, it remains unchanged from before—truly he is unstained and unburdened by worldly attachments. As I journeled through the western mountains near Luo, I happened upon the southern temple where Monk Chang dwells. Upon our first meeting, his joy was evident. He asked me to compose a record for the Wuuw Hall of Lingju Temple where he resides, and explained its purpose.

    The temple's Buddha Hall sits upon high ground in the center courtyard, with a pagoda. To the left stands a cloister, to the right the refectory. But the left side was near and crowded while the right lay distant—the layout was unbalanced. Thus the Wuuw Hall was erected to the left of the refectory, bringing harmony to the spacing on both sides. The structure, measured by pillars, consists of five bays in three rows; measured by intervals, five bays in two rows—a skillful and novel creation. Work began in the eighth month of Xinchi and was completed in the seventh month of this year. On the eighth month, the day of Jiazi, the sangha held a dedication ceremony. With this hall now in place, the refectory's left side, though still confined, can be relocated to the right, achieving perfect balance in arrangement and proportion. Yet the work may require strength that cannot be sustained, and thus reliance must be placed on those who come after—such was the master's intention.

    I observe that because the master's faith is steadfast, his reputation grows daily; because his dedication to virtue is unwavering, his projects bear fruit. Among all who uphold the sangha and establish the dharma, there are many, yet no other monk dares aspire to such accomplishment. How much more so for Lingju Temple, which seeks nothing but the Way itself. Therefore, though times are troubled, the work never ceases. Honoring the wishes of those above, maintaining the pure regulations, nurturing the next generation of practitioners—all pursued as though fearful of falling short. Truly, the master's diligence of spirit is admirable. How could I dare refuse to write this record to inform his successors? As for the meaning of Wuuw itself, those who dwell in this hall shall understand it well. Such matters need not be expounded here.

    Written in the renyin year of Zhizhen.
  footnotes:
    - Wuuw (無無) literally means 'non-non' or 'emptiness of emptiness,' a Buddhist philosophical concept referring to the ultimate reality beyond dualistic thinking.
    - The nine mountains (九山) refers to the nine major Zen temples of Korea.
    - The Lo River (洛水) in this context refers to the area near the royal court.
    - Zhizhen (至正) was a reign period of the Yuan Dynasty (1341-1368).
